{
  "answer": "**Cynewulf signed three surviving poems—*Elene*, *Juliana*, and *The Fates of the Apostles* (not in this corpus)—with a runic acrostic at the end of each.**[^1][^2] These are passages of personal reflection on sin, salvation, and life's transience, where the first character of each successive line forms a rune spelling his name: **C Y N E W U L F** (in futhorc runes: ᚳᚣᚾᛖᚹᚢᛚᚠ).[^3][^4]\n\nThis acrostic convention is subtle: the runes are integrated into alliterative verse as the first letters (often capitalized in modern editions), visible only when read vertically as a name-signature (a \"runespoem\"). It identifies the poet anonymously amid pious meditation, blending authorship with Christian humility.[^1][^2]\n\n*Andreas* (also attributed to Cynewulf) lacks this signature.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, chapter 1 (transliteration), [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/transliteration/#p-624562). The signature begins: \"A was secg... C drusende... Y gnornode / N gefera... E fore... W is... U was... L toglideth... F aghwam...\"\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, chapter 1 (transliteration), [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/transliteration/#p-01394b). The signature: \"Yeomor hweorfeth C Y ond N, / Chyning... E W ond U / ... L F beofath...\"\n\n[^3]: The runes match standard Anglo-Saxon futhorc; transliterations use Latin equivalents (e.g., \"C\" for ᚳ/cen, \"Y\" for ᚣ/yr, etc.).\n\n[^4]: In *Elene*: \"enge rune\" references runes explicitly in the signature.[^1]\n\n[^5]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, chapter 1 (transliteration), [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/transliteration/#p-992aeb). No matching acrostic or \"rune\" in signature context.",
